Hey Andrei,

/* from gtktreemodel.h */
#define GTK_TYPE_TREE_PATH             (gtk_tree_path_get_type ())
typedef struct _GtkTreePath         GtkTreePath;

/* from gtktreemodel.c */
struct _GtkTreePath
{
  gint depth;
  gint *indices;
};

- okay so that means the properties can't be exposed, right?  Was there any
other reason for complexity, or am I missing something?

I've tried implementing GtkTreePath as a boxed object (which it is in GTK+),
and all seems groovy. Removing the ignores gives an extra 13 generated
methods that may or may not work out of the box (haven't tested all of them
yet) and a working constructor - one function's skipped.  get_iter() needs
an override still, partly because we don't want to pass it an empty iter
from PHP-GTK userspace and partly because our return value's different from
GTK's return value (ours being of course more sane).

%%
override gtk_tree_model_get_iter
PHP_METHOD
{
    GtkTreeIter iter;
    GtkTreePath *path;
    zval *php_path;

    NOT_STATIC_METHOD();

    if (!php_gtk_parse_args(ZEND_NUM_ARGS(), "O", &php_path,
gtktreepath_ce))
        return;

    path = (GtkTreePath *) PHPG_GBOXED(php_path);

    if (gtk_tree_model_get_iter(GTK_TREE_MODEL(PHPG_GOBJECT(this_ptr)),
&iter, path)) {
        gtk_tree_path_free(path);
        phpg_gboxed_new(&return_value, GTK_TYPE_TREE_ITER, &iter, TRUE, TRUE
TSRMLS_CC);
    }
}

- notice I'm not using the treepath marshalling here.

So my question really is, what was the intention behind the marshaller? -
because if it's not needed we'd better kill it, but if it _is_ needed it'd
help if I understood why.

- Steph

