Hi Andrei,

In php_gtk+_types.c, you have:

  static const uint STYLE_NUM_STATES = 5;

It's used to check the positive end of ranges in a couple of places against
a straight int, e.g.

  if (index < 0 || index >= STYLE_NUM_STATES) {

and as a counter, again positive, in one place, e.g.

  for (i = 0; i < STYLE_NUM_STATES; i++) {

The only reason I can see for it being declared as a uint at all is:

  static int style_helper_count_elements(zval *object, long *count
TSRMLS_DC)
  {
      *count = STYLE_NUM_STATES;
      return SUCCESS;
  }

If you were planning to implement style_helper_count_elements() fully and
declare STYLE_NUM_STATES from there, uint would make some kind of sense.  As
a constant, it makes no sense at all.

Can I kill it and get rid of my compiler warnings pliz?

- Steph

