Thursday, May 19, 2005, 8:13:19 PM, you wrote:
MF> Hi,

MF> I'm trying to set a custom cursor on a window, the operation should be
MF> the following in C:

MF> cursor = gdk_cursor_new (GDK_WATCH);
MF> gdk_window_set_cursor (GTK_WIDGET (mainwindow)->window, cursor);
MF> gdk_cursor_unref (cursor);

MF> I can create a new cursor with

MF> $c = new GdkCursor(Gdk::WATCH);

MF> but I can't find a way to call gdk_window_set_cursor correctly.

MF> It's defined as GdkWindow::set_cursor but refers to 'this_ptr' in the
MF> source, when there's no object context to call it from; calling it
MF> statically fails:

MF> gdk_window_set_cursor(GDK_WINDOW(PHPG_OBJECT(this_ptr)), cursor);

MF> any ideas?

MF> - Markus

This is what I do on a double click ctree window to show a watch:

if ($event->type == GDK_2BUTTON_PRESS){
  $ctree->freeze();
  $c = 150; //watch
  $c = $c & 0xfe;
  $cursor = gdk::cursor_new($c);
  $window = $ctree->window;
  $window->set_cursor($cursor);
  //give it a chance to paint new cursor
  while(gtk::events_pending()) gtk::main_iteration();

  //do file loading stuff here
  .
  .
  .
  $window = $ctree->window;
  $window->set_cursor(); //default
  $ctree->thaw();
}

-- 
regards,
Tom

